  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 21.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "- To be kept for the decision of the emperor",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "to be reserved unto the hearing of Augustus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V.; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "should",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "might",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The decision",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "διαγνῶσις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", here only in the New Testament; but it is used in this sense in Wisd. 3:18 (\"the day of trial,\" or \"hearing,\" A.V.), and by Josephus ('Ant. Jud.,' 15. 3:8). For the verb ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "διαγινώσκω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 23:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 24:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", notes. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The emperor",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "τοῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "Σεβαστοῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); rather, as the A.V., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Augustus. Augustus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " was the title conferred by the senate upon Octavius Caesar,  ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "date",
        "text": "B.C. 27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", whom we commonly designate ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Augustus Caesar.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " It became afterwards the distinctive title of the reigning emperor, and, after the end of the second century, sometimes of two or even three co-emperors, and was now berne by Nero. Its Greek equivalent was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "Σεβαστός",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Augustus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " may be derived, as Ovid says, from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "augeo",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "faustus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "farce",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and be kindred with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "augur",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and mean one blest and aggrandized of God, and so, full of majesty. It is spoken of all holy things, temples and the like, \"Et queocunque sua Jupiter auget ope\" (Ovid, 'Fast.,' 1:609); and, as Ovid says in the same passage, is a title proper to the gods. For, comparing it with the names of the greatest Roman families, Maximus, Magnus, Torquatus, Corvus, etc., their names, he says, bespeak human honors, but of Augustus, he says, \"Hie socium summo cum Jove nomen habet.\" And so the Greek ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "Σεβαστός",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " bespeaks a veneration closely akin to adoration. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Caesar",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", originally the name of a family of the Juliagens, became the name of Octavius Caesar Augustus, as the adopted son of Julius Caesar; then of Tiberius, as the adopted son of Augustus; and then of the successors of Tiberius, Caligula, Claudius, and Nero, who had by descent or adoption some relationship to C. Julius Caesar the great dictator. After Nero, succeeding emperors usually prefixed the name of Caesar to their other names, and placed that of Augustus after them. AElius Verus, adopted by Hadrian, was the first person who bore the name of Caesar without being emperor. From this time it became usual for the heir to the throne to bear the name; and later, for many of the emperor's kindred to be so called. It was, in fact, a title of honor conferred by the emperor. Acts 25:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Of the Emperor (τοῦ Σεβαστοῦ)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lit., the august one; hence a translation of Augustus, which was not a proper name, but a title of the Roman emperors. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
